questions.question: Given the vector $\alpha = \hat{i} - \hat{j} + 2\hat{k}$ and a vector $\beta$ that satisfies the conditions $\alpha \times \beta = 2\hat{i} - \hat{k}$ and $\alpha \cdot \beta = 3$, determine the projection of vector $\beta$ onto the vector $(\alpha - \beta)$.

$$
\begin{array}{l}
\text{Match List I with List II} \\
\\
\begin{array}{|c|l|c|l|}
\hline
& \text{LIST I} & & \text{LIST II} \\
\hline
\text{A.} & \text{Torque} & \text{I.} & \left[M^1 L^1 T^{-2} A^{-2}\right] \\
\text{B.} & \text{Magnetic field} & \text{II.} & \left[L^2 A^1\right] \\
\text{C.} & \text{Magnetic moment} & \text{III.} & \left[M^1 T^{-2} A^{-1}\right] \\
\text{D.} & \text{Permeability of free space} & \text{IV.} & \left[M^1 L^2 T^{-2}\right] \\
\hline
\end{array}
\\
\\
\text{Choose the correct answer from the options given below:}
\end{array}
$$

A passenger sitting in train $\alpha$ observes another train $\beta$ moving in the opposite direction for $8 \, \text{s}$. If the velocity of train $\beta$ is $15 \, \text{m/s}$ and its length is $320 \, \text{m}$, determine the velocity of train $\alpha$ in $\text{m/s}$.

Truck $\alpha$ is traveling with a velocity $\vec{v}_{\alpha} = 30\hat{i} + 50\hat{j}$ km/h. At the same moment, Truck $\beta$ is located $80$ km east and $150$ km north of Truck $\alpha$ and is moving due west at $10$ km/h. Determine the time, in hours and minutes, at which the distance between the two trucks will be at a minimum.

As shown in the figure, a particle is moving with constant speed $v = \pi \text{ m/s}$ along a circular path of radius $R$. Considering its motion from point $A$ to point $B$ where the angle subtended at the center is $120^\circ$, the magnitude of the average velocity is:

In the arrangement shown in the figure, the mass of block $B$ and $A$ is $2m$ and $m$ respectively. The surface between $B$ and the floor is smooth. Block $B$ is connected to block $C$ by means of a string-pulley system. If the whole system is released, then find the minimum value of mass of block $C$ so that $A$ remains stationary w.r.t. $B$. The coefficient of friction between $A$ and $B$ is $\mu$.

Three objects A, B and C are kept in a straight line on a frictionless horizontal surface. The masses of A, B and C are $m, 2m$ and $2m$ respectively. A moves towards B with a speed of $9$ m/s and makes an elastic collision with it. Thereafter B makes a completely inelastic collision with C. All motions occur along the same straight line. The final speed of C is:

A block of mass $m = 1$ kg slides with velocity $v = 5$ m/s on a frictionless horizontal surface and collides elastically with a uniform vertical rod as shown. The rod is pivoted about $O$ and swings as a result of the collision making angle $\theta$ before momentarily coming to rest. If the rod has mass $M = 2$ kg and length $l = 1$ m, the value of $\theta$ is approximately (take $g = 10$ m/s$^2$, $\cos^{-1}(0.2) \approx 78^\circ$):

A structural engineer is inspecting the steel girders of a bridge during an extreme heatwave where temperatures have risen significantly. If the engineer models the elasticity of the steel using Young's modulus ($Y$), how will the increase in thermal energy affect the stiffness of these girders?
questions.option_a: The Young's modulus increases as atoms bond more tightly.
questions.option_b: The Young's modulus remains constant regardless of thermal energy.
questions.option_c: The Young's modulus decreases as interatomic vibrations increase.
questions.option_d: The Young's modulus first increases then decreases sharply.

questions.question: A bimetallic strip consists of metals A and B. It is mounted rigidly as shown. The metal A has higher coefficient of expansion compared to that of metal B. When the bimetallic strip is placed in a cold bath, it will :

A certain amount of gas of volume $V$ at $27^{\circ} \text{C}$ temperature and pressure $2 \times 10^{7} \text{ Nm}^{-2}$ expands isothermally until its volume gets doubled. Later it expands adiabatically until its volume gets redoubled. The final pressure of the gas will be (Use $\gamma=1.5$):
The density ($\rho$) versus pressure ($P$) of a given mass of an ideal gas is shown at two temperatures $T_1$ and $T_2$. Then the relation between $T_1$ and $T_2$ is:

A block of mass $\text{5kg}$ oscillates along the $x$-axis in simple harmonic motion according to the equation $x = a \sin(\omega t)$. If the momentum of the block is $p$ and its displacement is $x$, determine the geometric nature of the $p$-$x$ graph.
questions.option_a: A straight line with a slope of $5\omega$

questions.question: Two wires $W_1$ and $W_2$ have the same radius $r$ and respective densities $\rho_1$ and $\rho_2$ such that $\rho_2 = 4\rho_1$. They are joined together at the point $O$, as shown in the figure. The combination is used as a sonometer wire and kept under tension $T$. The point $O$ is midway between the two bridges ($B_1$ and $B_2$). When a stationary wave is set up in the composite wire, the joint is found to be a node. The ratio of the number of antinodes formed in $W_1$ to $W_2$ is: (Assume negligible separation between wall and $B_1$, pulley and $B_2$)

A bar magnet has a time period of oscillation $t$ seconds in a vibration magnetometer. The magnet is cut along its length into three equal parts, and these parts are then placed on top of each other with their like poles together. If the time period of this new combination is $2/3$ seconds, determine the value of the initial time period $t$ in seconds.

Figure shows a circuit that contains three identical resistors with resistance $R = 9.0\ \Omega$ each, two identical inductors with inductance $L = 2.0\ \text{mH}$ each, and an ideal battery with emf $\varepsilon = 18\ \text{V}$. The current $i$ through the battery just after the switch closed is:

An electromagnetic wave is propagating through vacuum along the $+z$-axis. A physicist represents the associated electric field ($\vec{E}$) and magnetic field ($\vec{B}$) using their vector components. Which of the following sets of equations correctly represents these fields, where $k$ is the wave number and $\omega$ is the angular frequency?

A transparent block $A$ having refractive index $\mu_2 = 1.25$ is surrounded by another medium of refractive index $\mu_1 = 1.0$ as shown in the figure. A light ray is incident on the flat face of the block with incident angle $\theta$ as shown in the figure. What is the maximum value of $\theta$ for which light suffers total internal reflection at the top surface of the block?

In the context of Young's Double Slit Experiment (YDSE), consider the following two statements regarding the angular separation of fringes:

$\pmb{\text{Statement I:}}$ If the screen is moved further away from the plane of the slits, the angular separation of the fringes remains constant.
$\pmb{\text{Statement II:}}$ If the monochromatic light source is replaced by another source with a larger wavelength, the angular separation of the fringes decreases.

Choose the correct assessment of these statements from the options provided.
questions.option_a: Both Statement I and Statement II are true.
questions.option_b: Statement I is true but Statement II is false.
questions.option_c: Statement I is false but Statement II is true.
questions.option_d: Both Statement I and Statement II are false.

questions.question: A theoretical hydrogen-like atom is formed where the orbiting electron is replaced by a subatomic particle $\text{x}$. This atom has a resulting radius of $2.5 \times 10^{-13} \, \text{m}$. Calculate the total atomic volume of one mole of such atoms in $\text{m}^3$. (Given: $\pi = 3.14$ and Avogadro's number $N_A = 6.023 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}$)

A body of mass $2$ kg is driven by an engine delivering a constant power of $1$ J/s. The body starts from rest and moves in a straight line. After $9$ seconds, the body has moved a distance (in m) _______.

A heat engine operates between a hot reservoir at $540 \, \text{K}$ and a cold reservoir at $324 \, \text{K}$. During each cycle, the engine delivers $180 \, \text{J}$ of heat to the cold reservoir. If the heat engine takes $x \, \text{kJ}$ of heat from the hot reservoir per cycle, determine the value of $x$ to the nearest integer.

A parallel plate capacitor has plate area $100$ m$^2$ and plate separation of $10$ m. The space between the plates is filled up to a thickness $5$ m with a material of dielectric constant $K = 10$. The resultant capacitance of the system is $x$ pF. Given $\varepsilon_0 = 8.85 \times 10^{-12}$ F/m, the value of $x$ to the nearest integer is _____________.

A solenoid of radius $10 \, \text{cm}$ and length $24\pi \, \text{cm}$ carries a current of $0.29 \, \text{A}$. If the magnetic field inside the solenoid is measured to be $2.9 \times 10^{-4} \, \text{Tesla}$, determine the number of turns $n$ of the solenoid.

The maximum emf that can be induced in a circular coil of radius $8.0\, \text{cm}$ and $20$ turns, rotating at $50\, \text{rad/s}$ about its vertical diameter, is $60.3 \times 10^{-2}\, \text{V}$. If the coil is placed in a uniform horizontal magnetic field $B$, calculate the value of $B$ in $\text{mT}$. (Take $\pi = 3.14$)
A solution is prepared by dissolving $5.85 \text{ g}$ of $NaCl$ in $1 \text{ L}$ of water. Determine the total number of $Na^+$ and $Cl^-$ ions present in a $1 \text{ mL}$ sample of this solution.

Arrange the following isoelectronic species in the decreasing order of their ionic radii:

$$O^{2-}, F^-, Na^+, Mg^{2+}$$

Match the molecules or species in List I with their corresponding properties or shapes in List II:

$$\begin{array}{|l|l|} \hline \textbf{List I (Molecule/Species)} & \textbf{List II (Property/Shape)} \\ \hline A. \, SO_2Cl_2 & I. \, \text{Paramagnetic} \\ \hline B. \, NO & II. \, \text{Diamagnetic} \\ \hline C. \, NO_2^- & III. \, \text{Tetrahedral} \\ \hline D. \, I_3^- & IV. \, \text{Linear} \\ \hline \end{array}$$

Select the correct matching sequence from the options below:
questions.option_a: $A \rightarrow III; B \rightarrow I; C \rightarrow II; D \rightarrow IV$
questions.option_b: $A \rightarrow III; B \rightarrow II; C \rightarrow I; D \rightarrow IV$
questions.option_c: $A \rightarrow IV; B \rightarrow I; C \rightarrow II; D \rightarrow III$
questions.option_d: $A \rightarrow I; B \rightarrow III; C \rightarrow IV; D \rightarrow II$

questions.question:
Which of the following parameters represent path functions?

(A) $H - TS$
(B) $w$
(C) $q$
(D) $q + w$

Consider the equilibrium reaction:

$$A_2(g) + 3B_2(g) \rightleftharpoons 2AB_3(g)$$

The equilibrium constant for this process is $K_p$. If pure $AB_3$ is allowed to dissociate at a constant total pressure $P$, determine the expression for the partial pressure of $AB_3$ at equilibrium. (Assume $p_{AB_3} \ll P$ at equilibrium).

A $100$ mL sample of $0.2$ N $NaOH$ is mixed with $100$ mL of $0.1$ N $NH_4Cl$, and the resulting mixture is diluted to a final volume of $1$ L. Calculate the pH of the final solution. (Given: $pK_b$ for $NH_4OH = 4.75$)
If the pH of a saturated solution of strontium hydroxide, $Sr(OH)_2$, is $12.0$ at $298$ K, determine the value of its solubility product constant ($K_{sp}$).
Identify which of the following chemical equations represents a redox process:
Nitrogen exists as a diatomic molecule $N_2$, while phosphorus forms a tetraatomic $P_4$ molecule. Identify the primary reason for this difference in atomicity:
questions.option_a: Multiple bonding is highly favorable in heavy atoms like phosphorus.
questions.option_b: $p\pi-p\pi$ overlap is efficient in nitrogen but ineffective in phosphorus.
questions.option_c: Phosphorus possesses a triple bond similar to nitrogen.
questions.option_d: $p\pi-p\pi$ bonding strength increases down the group.

questions.question: In which pairs, the first ion is more stable than the second?
In a sulphonation process, $11.7 \text{ g}$ of benzene reacts to form $15 \text{ g}$ of benzenesulphonic acid. Calculate the approximate percentage yield of this reaction.

But-2-yne is treated with one equivalent of hydrogen gas under two distinct catalytic conditions to yield products A and B as shown in the reaction scheme below:

$$\text{Product B} \xleftarrow{\text{Na, liq. } \text{NH}_3} \text{CH}_3\text{--C}\equiv\text{C--CH}_3 + \text{H}_2 \xrightarrow{\text{Pd/C, } \Delta} \text{Product A}$$

Consider the following statements regarding the physical and chemical properties of A and B:

P. The solubility of product A is higher than that of product B in polar solvents.
Q. Isomer A possesses a higher boiling point but a lower melting point compared to isomer B.
R. A exhibits higher polarity than B because the net dipole moment of A is equal to zero.
S. The rate of electrophilic addition of $\text{Br}_2$ is faster for isomer B than for isomer A.

Which of the following identifies the incorrect statements?

A binary solution is formed by mixing $5$ moles of liquid $X$ and $10$ moles of liquid $Y$. The pure vapor pressures of $X$ and $Y$ are $63$ torr and $78$ torr, respectively. If the measured vapor pressure of the resulting solution is $70$ torr, which statement is correct?
questions.option_a: The solution exhibits positive deviation from Raoult's law.
questions.option_b: The solution exhibits negative deviation from Raoult's law.
questions.option_c: The total volume is greater than the sum of the individual volumes.

questions.question:
The rate law for a specific reaction is given by the expression:

$$\text{Rate} = k[A]^2[B]$$

Determine the factor by which the reaction rate changes if the concentration of $A$ is tripled while the concentration of $B$ remains constant.
Hex-4-ene-2-ol on treatment with PCC gives 'A' on reaction with sodium hypoiodite gives 'B', which on further heating with soda lime gives 'C'. The compound 'C' is

Following compounds are given:

(i) $CH_{3}CH_{2}OH$
(ii) $CH_{3}COCH_{3}$
(iii) $CH_{3}-CHOH-CH_{3}$
(iv) $CH_{3}OH$

Which of the above compound(s), on being warmed with iodine solution and $NaOH$, will give iodoform?
Which of the following compounds will undergo self-aldol condensation in the presence of cold dilute alkali?
Identify A in the following chemical reaction.

$\textbf{Statement-I:}$ Barfoed test can be used to distinguish glucose and galactose.
$\textbf{Statement-II:}$ Glucose is a monosaccharide while galactose is a disaccharide.

In the light of the above statements, choose the most appropriate answer from the options given below:
questions.option_a: Statement-I is true but statement-II is false
questions.option_b: Both Statement-I and statement-II are true
questions.option_c: Both statement-I and statement-II are false
questions.option_d: Statement-I is false but statement-II is true

questions.question:
When a mixture of $NaCl$ and $K_2Cr_2O_7$ is gently warmed with concentrated $H_2SO_4$:
(i) An orange-red vapour is evolved.
(ii) The vapour formed, when passed into $NaOH$ solution, gives a yellow solution of $Na_2CrO_4$.
(iii) Chromyl chloride gas is not formed.
(iv) $SnCl_4$ used instead of $NaCl$ also gives the same observations.

Identify which of the above statements are correct.
questions.option_d: None of the statements are correct

questions.question:
The number of the following orbitals which have electron density along the axis is:

$$p_x, p_y, p_z, d_{xy}, d_{yz}, d_{xz}, d_{z^2}, d_{x^2-y^2}$$

For the gaseous isomerization reaction $$CH_3NC(g) \rightleftharpoons CH_3CN(g)$$, the equilibrium constant $K_p$ is $100.0$ at $300$ K. The standard Gibbs free energy change is expressed as $\Delta_rG^\circ = -\alpha R$, where $R$ is the universal gas constant. Determine the value of $\alpha$ and report the result of $\alpha + 20$. (Given: $\ln 10 = 2.3$)

In Duma's method for the analysis of $C_2H_7N$, the oxidation occurs using Cupric Oxide ($CuO$). Determine twice the value of the stoichiometric coefficient of $CuO$ required for the complete combustion of one mole of this organic compound.

The conductivity of a weak acid HA of concentration $0.001\text{ mol L}^{-1}$ is $2.0 \times 10^{-5}\text{ S cm}^{-1}$. If $\Lambda_m^o(HA) = 190\text{ S cm}^{2}\text{ mol}^{-1}$, the ionization constant ($K_{a}$) of HA is equal to ______________ $\times 10^{-6}$. (Round off to the Nearest Integer)

In an experiment, 46 g of benzyl trimethyl ammonium bromide are produced from the reaction of benzylamine with bromomethane. If the number of moles of bromomethane consumed are a Ã— 10$^{-2}$ then the value of a is______. [Given: Atomic masses: C: 12.0 u, H: 1.0u, N: 14.0u, Br: 80.0u]

In a demographic study of 1000 subjects, it was observed that 100 individuals do not utilize any of the three devices: laptops, smartphones, or smartwatches. It is known that 80 subjects use all three. Furthermore, 150 individuals use both laptops and smartphones, 200 use both smartphones and smartwatches, and 200 use both laptops and smartwatches. If the number of individuals using only a laptop ($x$), only a smartphone ($y$), and only a smartwatch ($z$) are all equal, determine the value of $z$.
Suppose $x$ and $y$ are real coefficients such that $1 - 2i$ is a root of the quadratic equation $z^2 + xz + y = 0$. Determine the ordered pair $(x, y)$ and calculate the value of $x - y$.

Let $u, v, w$ be the three roots of the cubic equation $x^{3} + px + q = 0$. Given the conditions $vw = 1$ and $u = -1$, determine the numerical value of the expression $p^3 + 2q^3 - 3u^3 - 6v^3 - 8w^3$.
The Geometric Mean ($\pmb{\text{G.M.}}$) and Harmonic Mean ($\pmb{\text{H.M.}}$) of two positive numbers are $10$ and $8$ respectively. The numbers are:

Let the point $\left(\frac{11}{2}, \alpha\right)$ lie on or inside the triangle with sides $L_1: x+y=11$, $L_2: x+2y=16$, and $L_3: 2x+3y=29$. Then the product of the smallest and the largest values of $\alpha$ is equal to:
If two tangents drawn from a point $P$ to the parabola $y^{2} = 16(x - 3)$ are at right angles, then the locus of point $P$ is:
The locus of the mid point of the line segment joining the point $(4, 3)$ and the points on the ellipse $x^2 + 2y^2 = 4$ is an ellipse with eccentricity $e$. Find the value of $2e^2$.

Consider a hyperbola $\mathrm{H}$ having centre at the origin and foci on the $\mathrm{x}$-axis. Let $\mathrm{C}_1$ be the circle touching the hyperbola $\mathrm{H}$ and having the centre at the origin. Let $\mathrm{C}_2$ be the circle touching the hyperbola $\mathrm{H}$ at its vertex and having the centre at one of its foci. If areas (in sq units) of $C_1$ and $C_2$ are $36 \pi$ and $4 \pi$, respectively, then the length (in units) of latus rectum of $\mathrm{H}$ is
If $\lim_{x \to 1} \frac{x^2 - ax + b}{x - 1} = 5$, then the ordered pair $(a, b)$ is:
If $y = (x + \sqrt{1 + x^2})^n$, then find the value of $(1 + x^2) \frac{d^2y}{dx^2} + x \frac{dy}{dx}$ when $y = 4$ and $n = 10$.

In a manufacturing process, the probability that a component is rejected during a preliminary inspection is $1/3$. If it passes this inspection, the probability that it successfully functions in the final assembly is $3/4$. If three such components are selected independently, find the probability that all three function successfully in the final assembly.

Suppose the inverse trigonometric functions are restricted to their principal value ranges. Let $x$ and $y$ be real numbers satisfying $x, y \in [-1, 1]$. If the relation $\cos^{-1} x - \sin^{-1} y = \phi$ holds for some constant $\phi$ in the interval $[-\pi/2, \pi]$, find the minimum possible value of the expression $x^2 + y^2 + 2xy \sin \phi$.

Find the range of the real-valued function $f(x)$ defined as:
$$f(x) = \sin^{-1}\left(\frac{3x - 22}{2x - 19}\right) + \log_{e}\left(\frac{3x^2 - 8x + 5}{x^2 - 3x - 10}\right)$$
over its natural domain.
questions.option_b: $(\text{A specific real interval depending on } x \in (5, 8.2])$

questions.question: Let $A = \begin{pmatrix} \alpha & -1 \\ 6 & \beta \end{pmatrix}$ where $\alpha > 0$, $\det(A) = 0$, and $\alpha + \beta = 1$. If $I$ denotes the $2 \times 2$ identity matrix, find the determinant of the matrix $(I + A)^8$.

Let $f_{1}(x)$ and $f_{2}(x)$ be two differentiable functions on $[0, 2]$ such that $$f_{1}''(x) - f_{2}''(x) = 0$$Given the conditions $f_{1}'(1) = 2$, $f_{2}'(1) = 4$, $f_{1}(2) = 3$, and $f_{2}(2) = 9$, find the value of $|f_{1}(0) - f_{2}(0)|$.

If $\lim_{x \to \infty} \left( \left( \frac{e}{1 - e} \right) \left( \frac{1}{e} - \frac{x}{1 + x} \right) \right)^{x} = \alpha$, then the value of $\frac{\log_{e} \alpha}{1 + \log_{e} \alpha}$ is expressed in the form $e^{k}$. Find the value of $k$.

Suppose a differentiable function $f(\theta)$ satisfies the derivative relation $$f'(\theta) = \tan^{-1}(\sec \theta + \tan \theta)$$ for the interval $-\frac{\pi}{2} < \theta < \frac{\pi}{2}$. If the initial condition is given as $f(0) = 0$, determine the value of $f(4)$.
The area (in square units) of the region bounded by the parabola $y^2=4(x-2)$ and the line $y=2x-8$, is:

Let $y = y(x)$ be the solution of the differential equation $\frac{dy}{dx} = 2x(x + y)^3 - x(x + y) - 1$ with the initial condition $y(0) = 1$. Then, the value of $\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} + y\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)\right)^2$ is:

Consider two line segments in three-dimensional space. The first segment connects point $P(3, 4, 5)$ to point $Q(4, 6, 3)$, and the second segment connects point $R(-1, 2, 4)$ to point $S(1, 0, 5)$. Find the magnitude of the projection of the vector $\vec{PQ}$ onto the vector $\vec{RS}$.

Consider the set $\mathrm{A}$ containing all natural numbers $x$ satisfying the inequality $x^2-10x+9 \leq 0$, and the set $\mathrm{B}$ consisting of all perfect squares of natural numbers. Determine the total number of functions $f: \mathrm{A} \to \mathrm{B}$ such that for every element $x$ in $\mathrm{A}$, the condition $$f(x) \leq (x-3)^{2}+1$$ holds true.
If $16\sin(20Â°)\sin(40Â°)\sin(80Â°)$ is equal to $\sqrt{m}$, then find the value of $m$.

A nine digit number is formed from {1,2,3,4,5,7} such that the product of all digits is always 1920. If the total number of arrangements possible can be written as a!/b! where a and b are coprime, return mod of difference.

Consider two curves given by the equations $$x^2 - 6x + y^2 + 8 = 0 \ and \ x^2 - 8y + y^2 + 16 - k = 0$$, where $k > 0$. If these curves are tangent to each other at some point, report the sum of all possible values of $k$.

Consider a group of 7 students in a class. Their mean score in a mathematics test is 62, and the variance of their scores is 20. A student is considered to have failed the examination if their score is below 50 marks. Determine the maximum possible number of students who could fail under the worst-case scenario.
